            <h3>Myth: "Raw meat is dangerous and full of bacteria"</h3>
            <p>Truth: Dogs and cats have evolved to handle bacteria in raw meat. Their acidic stomach environment and quick digestion time naturally prevent harmful bacterial overgrowth. Commercial pet food recalls for salmonella and other contaminants are actually more common than issues with properly sourced raw food.</p>

            <h3>Myth: "Raw diets are nutritionally incomplete"</h3>
            <p>Truth: A properly formulated raw diet including muscle meat, organ meat, and edible bones provides complete nutrition. Many commercial raw food companies follow AAFCO guidelines and work with veterinary nutritionists.</p>

            <h3>Myth: "Raw feeding is too expensive"</h3>
            <p>Truth: While initial costs may seem higher, many pet owners save money long-term through reduced vet bills, smaller portions needed (due to higher bioavailability), and elimination of costly treats and supplements.</p>

            <h3>Myth: "Raw bones will break teeth"</h3>
            <p>Truth: RAW bones are soft and pliable. It's COOKED bones that become brittle and dangerous. Raw bones actually help clean teeth and provide essential nutrients like calcium and phosphorus.</p>
